==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rue
<hw>Rue</hw> <pr>(r⟦udd⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>rue</ets>,
L. <ets>ruta</ets>, akin to Gr. <grk>"ryth`</grk>; cf. AS.
<ets>r⟦umac⟧de</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A
perennial suffrutescent plant (<spn>Ruta graveolens</spn>), having a
strong, heavy odor and a bitter taste; herb of grace. It is used in
medicine.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then purged with euphrasy and <qex>rue</qex>⟦br⟧
The visual nerve, for he had much to see.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They [the exorcists] are to try the devil by holy water, incense,
sulphur, <qex>rue</qex>, which from thence, as we suppose, came to be
called herb of grace.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: Bitterness; disappointment; grief;
regret.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Goat's rue</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Goat</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Rue anemone</b></col>, <cd>a pretty springtime flower
(<spn>Thalictrum anemonides</spn>) common in the United States.</cd> --
<col><b>Wall rue</b></col>, <cd>a little fern (<spn>Asplenium
Ruta-muraria</spn>) common on walls in Europe.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rue
<hw>Rue</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Rued</conjf> <pr>(r⟦udd⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ruing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>rewen</ets>,
<ets>reouwen</ets>, to grive, make sorry, AS. <ets>hre⟦oacute⟧wan</ets>;
akin to OS. <ets>hrewan</ets>, D. <ets>rouwen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>hriuwan</ets>, G. <ets>reuen</ets>, Icel. <ets>hryggr</ets>
grieved, <ets>hryg⟦edh⟧</ets> sorrow. ⟦root⟧ 18. Cf.
<er>Ruth</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lament; to regret extremely;
to grieve for or over.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I wept to see, and <qex>rued</qex> it from my heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapmen.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy will⟦br⟧
Chose freely what it now so justly <qex>rues</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to grieve; to afflict.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧God wot, it <xex>rueth</xex> me.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To repent of, and withdraw from, as a bargain; to
get released from.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rue
<hw>Rue</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have
compassion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God so wisly [<it>i. e.</it>, truly] on my soul
<qex>rue</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which stirred men's hearts to <qex>rue</qex> upon them.</q>
<rj><qau>Ridley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel sorrow and regret; to repent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Work by counsel and thou shalt not <qex>rue</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old year, we'll dearly <qex>rue</qex> for you.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rue</ent>⟦br⟧

